[src:shared-array-buffer/crossoriginisolated] The **`crossOriginIsolated`** read-only property of the `Window` interface returns a boolean value that indicates whether the document is cross-origin isolated.
[src:shared-array-buffer/crossoriginisolated] A cross-origin isolated document only shares its browsing context group with same-origin documents in popups and navigations, and resources (both same-origin and cross-origin) that the document has opted into using via CORS (and COEP for `<iframe>`).
[src:shared-array-buffer/crossoriginisolated] The relationship between a cross-origin opener of the document or any cross-origin popups that it opens are severed.
[src:shared-array-buffer/crossoriginisolated] The document may also be hosted in a separate OS process alongside other documents with which it can communicate by operating on shared memory.
[src:shared-array-buffer/crossoriginisolated] This mitigates the risk of side-channel attacks and cross-origin attacks referred to as XS-Leaks.
[src:shared-array-buffer/crossoriginisolated] Access to the APIs must also be allowed by the `Permissions-Policy` `cross-origin-isolated`.
[src:shared-array-buffer/crossoriginisolated] Otherwise `crossOriginIsolated` property will return `false`, and the document will not be able to use the APIs listed above with reduced restrictions.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-arraybuffer] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-arraybuffer] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-arraybuffer] The **`ArrayBuffer`** object is used to represent a generic raw binary data buffer.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-arraybuffer] It is an array of bytes, often referred to in other languages as a "byte array".
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-arraybuffer] You cannot directly manipulate the contents of an `ArrayBuffer`; instead, you create one of the typed array objects or a `DataView` object which represents the buffer in a specific format, and use that to read and write the contents of the buffer.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-arraybuffer] The `ArrayBuffer()` constructor creates a new `ArrayBuffer` of the given length in bytes.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-arraybuffer] You can also get an array buffer from existing data, for example, from a Base64 string or from a local file.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-arraybuffer] `ArrayBuffer` objects can be made resizable by including the `maxByteLength` option when calling the `ArrayBuffer()` constructor.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-arraybuffer] You can query whether an `ArrayBuffer` is resizable and what its maximum size is by accessing its `resizable` and `maxByteLength` properties, respectively.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-arraybuffer] You can assign a new size to a resizable `ArrayBuffer` with a `resize()` call.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-arraybuffer] These features make resizing `ArrayBuffer`s more efficient — otherwise, you have to make a copy of the buffer with a new size.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-arraybuffer] It also gives JavaScript parity with WebAssembly in this regard (Wasm linear memory can be resized with `WebAssembly.Memory.prototype.grow()`).
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-arraybuffer] `ArrayBuffer` objects can be transferred between different execution contexts, like Web Workers or Service Workers, using the structured clone algorithm.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-arraybuffer] This is done by passing the `ArrayBuffer` as a transferable object in a call to `Worker.postMessage()` or `ServiceWorker.postMessage()`.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-arraybuffer] In pure JavaScript, you can also transfer the ownership of memory from one `ArrayBuffer` to another using its `transfer()` or `transferToFixedLength()` method.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-arraybuffer] When an `ArrayBuffer` is transferred, its original copy becomes *detached* — this means it is no longer usable.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-arraybuffer] At any moment, there will only be one copy of the `ArrayBuffer` that actually has access to the underlying memory.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-arraybuffer] You can check whether an `ArrayBuffer` is detached by its `detached` property.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-arraybuffer] The constructor function that is used to create derived objects.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-arraybuffer] Returns `true` if `arg` is one of the ArrayBuffer views, such as typed array objects or a `DataView`.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-arraybuffer] These properties are defined on `ArrayBuffer.prototype` and shared by all `ArrayBuffer` instances.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-arraybuffer] The size, in bytes, of the `ArrayBuffer`.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-arraybuffer] This is established when the array is constructed and can only be changed using the `ArrayBuffer.prototype.resize()` method if the `ArrayBuffer` is resizable.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-arraybuffer] The constructor function that created the instance object.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-arraybuffer] For `ArrayBuffer` instances, the initial value is the `ArrayBuffer` constructor.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-arraybuffer] Returns `true` if the `ArrayBuffer` has been detached (transferred), or `false` if not.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-arraybuffer] The read-only maximum length, in bytes, that the `ArrayBuffer` can be resized to.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-arraybuffer] This is established when the array is constructed and cannot be changed.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-arraybuffer] Returns `true` if the `ArrayBuffer` can be resized, or `false` if not.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-arraybuffer] The initial value of the `[Symbol.toStringTag]` property is the string `"ArrayBuffer"`.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-arraybuffer] This property is used in `Object.prototype.toString()`.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-arraybuffer] Resizes the `ArrayBuffer` to the specified size, in bytes.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-arraybuffer] Returns a new `ArrayBuffer` whose contents are a copy of this `ArrayBuffer`'s bytes from `begin` (inclusive) up to `end` (exclusive).
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-arraybuffer] If either `begin` or `end` is negative, it refers to an index from the end of the array, as opposed to from the beginning.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-arraybuffer] Creates a new `ArrayBuffer` with the same byte content as this buffer, then detaches this buffer.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-arraybuffer] Creates a new non-resizable `ArrayBuffer` with the same byte content as this buffer, then detaches this buffer.
