[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-atomics] The **`Atomics`** namespace object contains static methods for carrying out atomic operations.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-atomics] They are used with `SharedArrayBuffer` and `ArrayBuffer` objects.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-atomics] Unlike most global objects, `Atomics` is not a constructor.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-atomics] You cannot use it with the `new` operator or invoke the `Atomics` object as a function.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-atomics] All properties and methods of `Atomics` are static (just like the `Math` object).
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-atomics] When memory is shared, multiple threads can read and write the same data in memory.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-atomics] Atomic operations make sure that predictable values are written and read, that operations are finished before the next operation starts and that operations are not interrupted.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-atomics] The `wait()` and `notify()` methods are modeled on Linux futexes ("fast user-space mutex") and provide ways for waiting until a certain condition becomes true and are typically used as blocking constructs.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-atomics] The initial value of the `[Symbol.toStringTag]` property is the string `"Atomics"`.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-atomics] Adds the provided value to the existing value at the specified index of the array.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-atomics] Computes a bitwise AND on the value at the specified index of the array with the provided value.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-atomics] Stores a value at the specified index of the array, if it equals a value.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-atomics] Stores a value at the specified index of the array.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-atomics] An optimization primitive that can be used to determine whether to use locks or atomic operations.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-atomics] Returns `true` if an atomic operation on arrays of the given element size will be implemented using a hardware atomic operation (as opposed to a lock).
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-atomics] Returns the value at the specified index of the array.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-atomics] Notifies agents that are waiting on the specified index of the array.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-atomics] Returns the number of agents that were notified.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-atomics] Computes a bitwise OR on the value at the specified index of the array with the provided value.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-atomics] Provides a micro-wait primitive that hints to the CPU that the caller is spinning while waiting on access to a shared resource.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-atomics] This allows the system to reduce the resources allocated to the core (such as power) or thread, without yielding the current thread.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-atomics] Subtracts a value at the specified index of the array.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-atomics] Verifies that the specified index of the array still contains a value and sleeps awaiting or times out.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-atomics] If waiting is not allowed in the calling agent then it throws an exception.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-atomics] Waits asynchronously (i.e., without blocking, unlike `Atomics.wait`) on a shared memory location and returns an object representing the result of the operation.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-atomics] Computes a bitwise XOR on the value at the specified index of the array with the provided value.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-atomics] Note that these examples cannot be run directly from the console or an arbitrary web page, because `SharedArrayBuffer` is not defined unless its security requirements are met.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-atomics] A reading thread is sleeping and waiting on location 0 because the provided value matches what is stored at the provided index.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-atomics] The reading thread will not move on until the writing thread has called `Atomics.notify()` on position 0 of the provided typed array.
[src:shared-array-buffer/global-objects-atomics] Note that if, after being woken up, the value of location 0 has not been changed by the writing thread, the reading thread will **not** go back to sleep, but will continue on.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] That sequential history is a subset of the original unextended list.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] Informally, this means that the unmodified list of events is linearizable if and only if its invocations were serializable, but some of the responses of the serial schedule have yet to return.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] In a concurrent system, processes can access a shared object at the same time.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] Because multiple processes are accessing a single object, a situation may arise in which while one process is accessing the object, another process changes its contents.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] Making a system linearizable is one solution to this problem.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] In a linearizable system, although operations overlap on a shared object, each operation appears to take place instantaneously.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] Linearizability is a strong correctness condition, which constrains what outputs are possible when an object is accessed by multiple processes concurrently.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] It is a safety property which ensures that operations do not complete unexpectedly or unpredictably.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] If a system is linearizable it allows a programmer to reason about the system.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] Linearizability was first introduced as a consistency model by Herlihy and Wing in 1987.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] It encompassed more restrictive definitions of atomic, such as "an atomic operation is one which cannot be (or is not) interrupted by concurrent operations", which are usually vague about when an operation is considered to begin and end.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] An atomic object can be understood immediately and completely from its sequential definition, as a set of operations run in parallel which always appear to occur one after the other; no inconsistencies may emerge.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] Specifically, linearizability guarantees that the invariants of a system are *observed* and *preserved* by all operations: if all operations individually preserve an invariant, the system as a whole will.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] A concurrent system consists of a collection of processes communicating through shared data structures or objects.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] Linearizability is important in these concurrent systems where objects may be accessed by multiple processes at the same time and a programmer needs to be able to reason about the expected results.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] An execution of a concurrent system results in a *history*, an ordered sequence of completed operations.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] A *history* is a sequence of *invocations* and *responses* made of an object by a set of threads or processes.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] An invocation can be thought of as the start of an operation, and the response being the signaled end of that operation.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] Each invocation of a function will have a subsequent response.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] This can be used to model any use of an object.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] Suppose, for example, that two threads, A and B, both attempt to grab a lock, backing off if it's already taken.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] This would be modeled as both threads invoking the lock operation, then both threads receiving a response, one successful, one not.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] A *sequential* history is one in which all invocations have immediate responses; that is the invocation and response are considered to take place instantaneously.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] A sequential history should be trivial to reason about, as it has no real concurrency; the previous example was not sequential, and thus is hard to reason about.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] If an operation op1 completes (gets a response) before op2 begins (invokes), then op1 precedes op2 in $\sigma$ .
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] Note that the first two bullet points here match serializability: the operations appear to happen in some order.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] It is the last point which is unique to linearizability, and is thus the major contribution of Herlihy and Wing.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] Consider two ways of reordering the locking example above.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] Reordering B's invocation after A's response yields a sequential history.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] This is easy to reason about, as all operations now happen in an obvious order.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] However, it does not match the sequential definition of the object (it doesn't match the semantics of the program): A should have successfully obtained the lock, and B should have subsequently aborted.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] This is another correct sequential history.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] It is also a linearization since it matches the sequential definition.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] Note that the definition of linearizability only precludes responses that precede invocations from being reordered; since the original history had no responses before invocations, they can be reordered.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] Hence the original history is indeed linearizable.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] An object (as opposed to a history) is linearizable if all valid histories of its use can be linearized.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] This is a much harder assertion to prove.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] This history is not valid because there is a point at which both A and B hold the lock; moreover, it cannot be reordered to a valid sequential history without violating the ordering rule.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] This reordering is sensible provided there is no alternative means of communicating between A and B.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] Linearizability is better when considering individual objects separately, as the reordering restrictions ensure that multiple linearizable objects are, considered as a whole, still linearizable.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] This alternative is usually much easier to prove.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] It is also much easier to reason about as a user, largely due to its intuitiveness.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] This property of occurring instantaneously, or indivisibly, leads to the use of the term *atomic* as an alternative to the longer "linearizable".
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] In the examples below, the linearization point of the counter built on compare-and-swap is the linearization point of the first (and only) successful compare-and-swap update.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] The counter built using locking can be considered to linearize at any moment while the locks are held, since any potentially conflicting operations are excluded from running during that period.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] Processors have instructions that can be used to implement locking and lock-free and wait-free algorithms.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] The ability to temporarily inhibit interrupts, ensuring that the currently running process cannot be context switched, also suffices on a uniprocessor.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] Most processors include store operations that are not atomic with respect to memory.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] These include multiple-word stores and string operations.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] Should a high priority interrupt occur when a portion of the store is complete, the operation must be completed when the interrupt level is returned.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] The routine that processes the interrupt must not modify the memory being changed.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] It is important to take this into account when writing interrupt routines.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] When there are multiple instructions which must be completed without interruption, a CPU instruction which temporarily disables interrupts is used.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] This must be kept to only a few instructions and the interrupts must be re-enabled to avoid unacceptable response time to interrupts or even losing interrupts.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] This mechanism is not sufficient in a multi-processor environment since each CPU can interfere with the process regardless of whether interrupts occur or not.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] Further, in the presence of an instruction pipeline, uninterruptible operations present a security risk, as they can potentially be chained in an infinite loop to create a denial of service attack, as in the Cyrix coma bug.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] The C standard and SUSv3 provide `sig_atomic_t` for simple atomic reads and writes; incrementing or decrementing is not guaranteed to be atomic.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] More complex atomic operations are available in C11, which provides `stdatomic.h`.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] Compilers use the hardware features or more complex methods to implement the operations; an example is libatomic of GCC.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] The ARM instruction set provides `LDREX` and `STREX` instructions which can be used to implement atomic memory access by using exclusive monitors implemented in the processor to track memory accesses for a specific address.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] However, if a context switch occurs between calls to `LDREX` and `STREX`, the documentation notes that `STREX` will fail, indicating the operation should be retried.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] In the case of 64-bit ARMv8-A architecture, it provides `LDXR` and `STXR` instructions for byte, half-word, word, and double-word size.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] The easiest way to achieve linearizability is running groups of primitive operations in a critical section.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] Strictly, independent operations can then be carefully permitted to overlap their critical sections, provided this does not violate linearizability.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] Such an approach must balance the cost of large numbers of locks against the benefits of increased parallelism.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] Another approach, favoured by researchers (but not yet widely used in the software industry), is to design a linearizable object using the native atomic primitives provided by the hardware.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] This has the potential to maximise available parallelism and minimise synchronisation costs, but requires mathematical proofs which show that the objects behave correctly.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] A promising hybrid of these two is to provide a transactional memory abstraction.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] As with critical sections, the user marks sequential code that must be run in isolation from other threads.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] The implementation then ensures the code executes atomically.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] This style of abstraction is common when interacting with databases; for instance, when using the Spring Framework, annotating a method with @Transactional will ensure all enclosed database interactions occur in a single database transaction.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] Transactional memory goes a step further, ensuring that all memory interactions occur atomically.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] As with database transactions, issues arise regarding composition of transactions, especially database and in-memory transactions.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] A common theme when designing linearizable objects is to provide an all-or-nothing interface: either an operation succeeds completely, or it fails and does nothing.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] (ACID databases refer to this principle as atomicity.) If the operation fails (usually due to concurrent operations), the user must retry, usually performing a different operation.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] To demonstrate the power and necessity of linearizability we will consider a simple counter which different processes can increment.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] We would like to implement a counter object which multiple processes can access.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] Many common systems make use of counters to keep track of the number of times an event has occurred.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] The counter object can be accessed by multiple processes and has two available operations.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] Read - returns the current value stored in the counter without changing it.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] We will attempt to implement this counter object using shared registers.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] Our first attempt which we will see is non-linearizable has the following implementation using one shared register among the processes.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] This simple implementation is not linearizable, as is demonstrated by the following example.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] The second process writes the new value into the register, the register now has value 1.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] In the above example, two processes invoked an increment command, however the value of the object only increased from 0 to 1, instead of 2 as it should have.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] One of the increment operations was lost as a result of the system not being linearizable.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] The above example shows the need for carefully thinking through implementations of data structures and how linearizability can have an effect on the correctness of the system.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] To implement a linearizable or atomic counter object we will modify our previous implementation so **each process Pi will use its own register Ri**.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] This is similar to how grow-only counter CRDTs work.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] This implementation solves the problem with our original implementation.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] In this system the increment operations are linearized at the write step.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] The linearization point of an increment operation is when that operation writes the new value in its register Ri.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] The read operations are linearized to a point in the system when the value returned by the read is equal to the sum of all the values stored in each register Ri.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] In a real system, the operations can be more complex and the errors introduced extremely subtle.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] For example, reading a 64-bit value from memory may actually be implemented as two sequential reads of two 32-bit memory locations.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] If a process has only read the first 32 bits, and before it reads the second 32 bits the value in memory gets changed, it will have neither the original value nor the new value but a mixed-up value.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] Furthermore, the specific order in which the processes run can change the results, making such an error difficult to detect, reproduce and debug.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] Most systems provide an atomic compare-and-swap instruction that reads from a memory location, compares the value with an "expected" one provided by the user, and writes out a "new" value if the two match, returning whether the update succeeded.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] 4. retry if the value read in by the compare-and-swap did not match the value we originally read.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] Since the compare-and-swap occurs (or appears to occur) instantaneously, if another process updates the location while we are in-progress, the compare-and-swap is guaranteed to fail.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] Many systems provide an atomic fetch-and-increment instruction that reads from a memory location, unconditionally writes a new value (the old value plus one), and returns the old value.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] So CPU designs with both fetch-and-increment and compare-and-swap (or equivalent instructions) may be a better choice than ones with only one or the other.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] Another approach is to turn the naive algorithm into a critical section, preventing other threads from disrupting it, using a lock.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] This strategy works as expected; the lock prevents other threads from updating the value until it is released.
[src:shared-array-buffer/linearizability] However, when compared with direct use of atomic operations, it can suffer from significant overhead due to lock contention.
[src:shared-array-buffer/memory-barrier] In computing, a **memory barrier**, also known as a **membar**, **memory fence** or **fence instruction**, is a type of barrier instruction that causes a central processing unit (CPU) or compiler to enforce an ordering constraint on memory operations issued before and after the barrier instruction.
[src:shared-array-buffer/memory-barrier] This typically means that operations issued prior to the barrier are guaranteed to be performed before operations issued after the barrier.
[src:shared-array-buffer/memory-barrier] Memory barriers are necessary because most modern CPUs employ performance optimizations that can result in out-of-order execution.
[src:shared-array-buffer/memory-barrier] This reordering of memory operations (loads and stores) normally goes unnoticed within a single thread of execution, but can cause unpredictable behavior in concurrent programs and device drivers unless carefully controlled.
[src:shared-array-buffer/memory-barrier] The exact nature of an ordering constraint is hardware dependent and defined by the architecture's memory ordering model.
[src:shared-array-buffer/memory-barrier] Some architectures provide multiple barriers for enforcing different ordering constraints.
[src:shared-array-buffer/memory-barrier] Memory barriers are typically used when implementing low-level machine code that operates on memory shared by multiple devices.
[src:shared-array-buffer/memory-barrier] Such code includes synchronization primitives and lock-free data structures on multiprocessor systems, and device drivers that communicate with computer hardware.
[src:shared-array-buffer/memory-barrier] When a program runs on a single-CPU machine, the hardware performs the necessary bookkeeping to ensure that the program executes as if all memory operations were performed in the order specified by the programmer (program order), so memory barriers are not necessary.
[src:shared-array-buffer/memory-barrier] However, when the memory is shared with multiple devices, such as other CPUs in a multiprocessor system, or memory-mapped peripherals, out-of-order access may affect program behavior.
[src:shared-array-buffer/memory-barrier] For example, a second CPU may see memory changes made by the first CPU in a sequence that differs from program order.
[src:shared-array-buffer/memory-barrier] A program is run via a process which can be multi-threaded (i.e. a software thread such as pthreads as opposed to a hardware thread).
[src:shared-array-buffer/memory-barrier] Different processes do not share a memory space so this discussion does not apply to two programs, each one running in a different process (hence a different memory space).
[src:shared-array-buffer/memory-barrier] It applies to two or more (software) threads running in a single process (i.e. a single memory space where multiple software threads share a single memory space).
[src:shared-array-buffer/memory-barrier] Multiple software threads, within a single process, may run concurrently on a multi-core processor.
[src:shared-array-buffer/memory-barrier] Initially, memory locations x and f both hold the value 0.
[src:shared-array-buffer/memory-barrier] The software thread running on processor #1 loops while the value of f is zero, then it prints the value of x.
[src:shared-array-buffer/memory-barrier] The software thread running on processor #2 stores the value 42 into x and then stores the value 1 into f.
[src:shared-array-buffer/memory-barrier] Pseudo-code for the two program fragments is shown below.
[src:shared-array-buffer/memory-barrier] The steps of the program correspond to individual processor instructions.
[src:shared-array-buffer/memory-barrier] One might expect the print statement to always print the number "42"; however, if thread #2's store operations are executed out-of-order, it is possible for f to be updated *before* x, and the print statement might therefore print "0".
[src:shared-array-buffer/memory-barrier] Similarly, thread #1's load operations may be executed out-of-order and it is possible for x to be read *before* f is checked, and again the print statement might therefore print an unexpected value.
[src:shared-array-buffer/memory-barrier] For most programs neither of these situations is acceptable.
[src:shared-array-buffer/memory-barrier] A memory barrier must be inserted before thread #2's assignment to f to ensure that the new value of x is visible to other processors at or prior to the change in the value of f.
[src:shared-array-buffer/memory-barrier] Another important point is a memory barrier must also be inserted before thread #1's access to x to ensure the value of x is not read prior to seeing the change in the value of f.
[src:shared-array-buffer/memory-barrier] If the processor's store operations are executed out-of-order, the hardware module may be triggered before data is ready in memory.
[src:shared-array-buffer/memory-barrier] For another illustrative example (a non-trivial one that arises in actual practice), see double-checked locking.
[src:shared-array-buffer/memory-barrier] In the case of the ARM architecture family, the DMB, DSB and ISB instructions are used.
[src:shared-array-buffer/memory-barrier] In the case of the RISC-V architecture, the FENCE instruction is used.
[src:shared-array-buffer/memory-barrier] In the case of the x86 architecture, the MFENCE, LFENCE, and SFENCE instructions are used.
[src:shared-array-buffer/memory-barrier] Multithreaded programs usually use synchronization primitives provided by a high-level programming environment—such as Java or .NET—or an application programming interface (API) such as POSIX Threads or Windows API.
[src:shared-array-buffer/memory-barrier] Synchronization primitives such as mutexes and semaphores are provided to synchronize access to resources from parallel threads of execution.
[src:shared-array-buffer/memory-barrier] These primitives are usually implemented with the memory barriers required to provide the expected memory visibility semantics.
[src:shared-array-buffer/memory-barrier] In such environments explicit use of memory barriers is not generally necessary.
[src:shared-array-buffer/memory-barrier] Memory barrier instructions address reordering effects only at the hardware level.
[src:shared-array-buffer/memory-barrier] Compilers may also reorder instructions as part of the program optimization process.
[src:shared-array-buffer/memory-barrier] Although the effects on parallel program behavior can be similar in both cases, in general, it is necessary to take separate measures to inhibit compiler reordering optimizations for data that may be shared by multiple threads of execution.
[src:shared-array-buffer/memory-barrier] In C and C++, the volatile keyword was intended to allow C and C++ programs to directly access memory-mapped I/O.
[src:shared-array-buffer/memory-barrier] Memory-mapped I/O generally requires that the reads and writes specified in source code happen in the exact order specified with no omissions.
[src:shared-array-buffer/memory-barrier] Omissions or reorderings of reads and writes by the compiler would break the communication between the program and the device accessed by memory-mapped I/O.
[src:shared-array-buffer/memory-barrier] A C or C++ compiler may not omit reads from and writes to volatile memory locations, nor may it reorder read/writes relative to other such actions for the same volatile location (variable).
[src:shared-array-buffer/memory-barrier] The keyword volatile *does not guarantee a memory barrier* to enforce cache-consistency.
[src:shared-array-buffer/memory-barrier] Therefore, the use of volatile alone is not sufficient to use a variable for inter-thread communication on all systems and processors.
[src:shared-array-buffer/memory-barrier] The C and C++ standards prior to C11 and C++11 do not address multiple threads (or multiple processors), and as such, the usefulness of volatile depends on the compiler and hardware.
[src:shared-array-buffer/sharedarraybuffer] The **`SharedArrayBuffer`** object is used to represent a generic raw binary data buffer, similar to the `ArrayBuffer` object, but in a way that they can be used to create views on shared memory.
[src:shared-array-buffer/sharedarraybuffer] A `SharedArrayBuffer` is not a Transferable Object, unlike an `ArrayBuffer` which is transferable.
[src:shared-array-buffer/sharedarraybuffer] To share memory using `SharedArrayBuffer` objects from one agent in the cluster to another (an agent is either the web page's main program or one of its web workers), `postMessage` and structured cloning is used.
[src:shared-array-buffer/sharedarraybuffer] The structured clone algorithm accepts `SharedArrayBuffer` objects and typed arrays mapped onto `SharedArrayBuffer` objects.
[src:shared-array-buffer/sharedarraybuffer] In both cases, the `SharedArrayBuffer` object is transmitted to the receiver resulting in a new, private `SharedArrayBuffer` object in the receiving agent (just as for `ArrayBuffer`).
[src:shared-array-buffer/sharedarraybuffer] However, the shared data block referenced by the two `SharedArrayBuffer` objects is the same data block, and a side effect to the block in one agent will eventually become visible in the other agent.
[src:shared-array-buffer/sharedarraybuffer] Shared memory can be created and updated simultaneously in workers or the main thread.
[src:shared-array-buffer/sharedarraybuffer] Depending on the system (the CPU, the OS, the Browser) it can take a while until the change is propagated to all contexts.
[src:shared-array-buffer/sharedarraybuffer] To synchronize, atomic operations are needed.
[src:shared-array-buffer/sharedarraybuffer] Shared memory and high-resolution timers were effectively disabled at the start of 2018 in light of Spectre.
[src:shared-array-buffer/sharedarraybuffer] In 2020, a new, secure approach has been standardized to re-enable shared memory.
[src:shared-array-buffer/sharedarraybuffer] To use shared memory your document must be in a secure context and cross-origin isolated.
[src:shared-array-buffer/sharedarraybuffer] When cross-origin isolated, `postMessage()` no longer throws for `SharedArrayBuffer` objects, and shared memory across threads is therefore available.
[src:shared-array-buffer/sharedarraybuffer] `WebAssembly.Memory` objects can be created with the `shared` constructor flag.
[src:shared-array-buffer/sharedarraybuffer] When this flag is set to `true`, the constructed `Memory` object can be shared between workers via `postMessage()`, just like `SharedArrayBuffer`, and the backing `buffer` of the `Memory` object is a `SharedArrayBuffer`.
[src:shared-array-buffer/sharedarraybuffer] Therefore, the requirements listed above for sharing a `SharedArrayBuffer` between workers also apply to sharing a `WebAssembly.Memory`.
[src:shared-array-buffer/sharedarraybuffer] The WebAssembly Threads proposal also defines a new set of atomic instructions.
[src:shared-array-buffer/sharedarraybuffer] Just as `SharedArrayBuffer` and its methods are unconditionally enabled (and only sharing between threads is gated on the new headers), the WebAssembly atomic instructions are also unconditionally allowed.
[src:shared-array-buffer/sharedarraybuffer] `SharedArrayBuffer` objects can be made growable by including the `maxByteLength` option when calling the `SharedArrayBuffer()` constructor.
[src:shared-array-buffer/sharedarraybuffer] You can query whether a `SharedArrayBuffer` is growable and what its maximum size is by accessing its `growable` and `maxByteLength` properties, respectively.
[src:shared-array-buffer/sharedarraybuffer] You can assign a new size to a growable `SharedArrayBuffer` with a `grow()` call.
[src:shared-array-buffer/sharedarraybuffer] These features make growing `SharedArrayBuffer`s more efficient — otherwise, you have to make a copy of the buffer with a new size.
[src:shared-array-buffer/sharedarraybuffer] For security reasons, `SharedArrayBuffer`s cannot be reduced in size, only grown.
[src:shared-array-buffer/sharedarraybuffer] Creates a new `SharedArrayBuffer` object.
[src:shared-array-buffer/sharedarraybuffer] Returns the constructor used to construct return values from `SharedArrayBuffer` methods.
[src:shared-array-buffer/sharedarraybuffer] These properties are defined on `SharedArrayBuffer.prototype` and shared by all `SharedArrayBuffer` instances.
[src:shared-array-buffer/sharedarraybuffer] This is established when the array is constructed and can only be changed using the `SharedArrayBuffer.prototype.grow()` method if the `SharedArrayBuffer` is growable.
[src:shared-array-buffer/sharedarraybuffer] For `SharedArrayBuffer` instances, the initial value is the `SharedArrayBuffer` constructor.
[src:shared-array-buffer/sharedarraybuffer] Returns `true` if the `SharedArrayBuffer` can be grown, or `false` if not.
[src:shared-array-buffer/sharedarraybuffer] The read-only maximum length, in bytes, that the `SharedArrayBuffer` can be grown to.
[src:shared-array-buffer/sharedarraybuffer] The initial value of the `[Symbol.toStringTag]` property is the string `"SharedArrayBuffer"`.
[src:shared-array-buffer/sharedarraybuffer] Grows the `SharedArrayBuffer` to the specified size, in bytes.
[src:shared-array-buffer/sharedarraybuffer] Returns a new `SharedArrayBuffer` whose contents are a copy of this `SharedArrayBuffer`'s bytes from `begin`, inclusive, up to `end`, exclusive.
[src:shared-array-buffer/sharedarraybuffer] Note that these examples cannot be run directly from the console or and arbitrary web page, because `SharedArrayBuffer` is not defined unless its security requirements are met.
